    thinking: "**Defining App Component Purpose**\n\nI\'ve decided that `src/App.tsx` will be the central orchestration point. It\'s designed to manage the application\'s core state engine. I\'ll load the initial application state from `LocalStorage` on component mount, likely using a function called `getDB()`. Key tracked elements will include `currentView`, with an initial value of \"landing\".\n\n\n**Orchestrating App Lifecycle**\n\nI\'m now focusing on `src/App.tsx` and its role as the app\'s central hub. I\'m building out the `activeGuildId` and `prefilledGuildId` state variables. Upon mount, I\'ll be listening for query parameters (like `?invite=FF-EVOS-21`). If an invite code is present, I\'ll set `prefilledGuildId` and adjust `currentView` to \"register-member\". The application now has a clean and realistic join-link integration! I plan to flesh out actions: `handleEnterGuild` and `handleCreateGuild`.\n\n\n**Defining Core User Actions**\n\nI\'m solidifying the core user actions that will drive this app. I\'m building out a series of handlers: `handleRegisterMember`, `handleAddPost`, `handleEditPost`, `handleDeletePost`, `handleUpdateRole`, `handleKicked`, and `handleResetDB`. Each handler corresponds to a specific action and manages calls to the database. These are looking excellent.\n\n\n\n"
    modified_response: "I will now implement `/src/App.tsx` to handle the routing state machine. It will load state from LocalStorage on mount, check for an invite code (`?invite=ID_GUILD`) in the URL search parameters to pre-fill the enlistment form, orchestrate all DB persistence actions (Guild Registration, Member Recruitment, Post Announcements, Role Upgrades, and Kicks), and render the responsive frame complete with our real-time visual Database Inspector."
